A permutation $\sigma$ is called ___even___ if $\sgn(\sigma) = 1$, and ___odd___ if $\sgn(\sigma) = -1$.

**Proposition:** $\sigma$ is even (resp. odd) iff it decomposes into an even (resp. odd) number of transpositions.

*Proof:* First observe that every transposition is odd. (This is easy to see by counting the inversions explicitly.) Then observe that when a permutation is multiplied by a transposition, its sign changes. **QED**

