## Groups of Order $pq$

**Corollary:** For every pair of primes $p$ and $q$, there are at most two groups of order $pq$ up to isomorphism.

*Proof:* WLOG let $p < q$. Observe that the number $N_q$ of Sylow $q$-subgroups must divide $pq$, hence it must divide $p$ (since it cannot divide $q$, being congruent to $1 \mod q$). Thus we must have $N_q = 1$. Let $A$ be the unique Sylow $q$-subgroup of $G$. Then $A \trianglelefteq G$.

Now we also have that $N_p$ is divible by $pq$ and $N_p \equiv 1 \mod p$. Thus the only possibilities are $N_p = 1$, or $N_p = q$ if $q \equiv 1 \mod p$. If $N_p = 1$, then by letting $B$ be the unique Sylow $p$-subgroup of $G$, we obtain an isomorphism $G \cong A \times B \cong \Z_p \times \Z_q \cong \Z_{pq}$.

**Homework #4.** Prove that $\Z_p \times \Z_q \cong \Z_{pq}$ when $p$ and $q$ are distinct primes.

